eone of Irish origin, from Old French <i>Ireis</i> or Middle English <i>Irish</i> ‘Irish’, Latinized as <i>Hiberniens(is)</i>. Compare   Ireland  ."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert Ireland was born in 1218, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger de Ireland, was 33 and his mother, Mrs Ireland, was 33. He married Beatrice Daresby in 1242, in Warton, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1247, in Warton, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 29."},"et":{"1218–1247":"1218–1247","1223–1247":"1223–1247","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","1244–Male":"1244–Surnud","1247–1320":"1247–1320","1185–1217":"1185–1217","1185–Female":"1185–Surnud","1217":"1217","1247":"1247","1223":"1223","1244":"1244","1320":"1320","1242":"1242","about 1247":"umbes 1247","about 1244":"umbes 1244","1185":"1185","1218":"1218","Warton, Lancashire, England":"Warton, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hutt, Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, 